Selecting (The) Target Segment(s)¶

Users of the market segmentation (McDonald's management) can now move on to build a segment evaluation plot using the knock-out criterion and segment attractiveness criteria described in Step 2.

Customising the Marketing Mix¶

The marketing mix is designed in Step 9. For instance, if McDonald's managers choose to concentrate on segment 3 (young customers who enjoy McDonald's, think the food is delicious and tasty, but perceive it to be fairly expensive), they may decide to offer an MCSUPERBUDGET line to specifically address their segment's expectations regarding price (4Ps: Price). The benefit of such a strategy may be that segment 3 members grow to be devoted patrons who, when they begin earning more money, will no longer be concerned about the price and switch to the standard McDonald's variety of products. The product features of the MCSUPERBUDGET range would need to be distinctly different from the main range (4Ps: Product) in order to avoid cannibalising the main range. The next step would be to identify the communication channels that segment 3 members frequently utilise to spread the word about the MCSUPERBUDGET line's availability (4Ps: Promotion). Given that all McDonald's food is offered in McDonald's outlets, distribution channels (4Ps: Place) would have to be the same for all of the McDonald's products. To avoid cannibalising its main product line, McDonald's management may want to consider adding an MCSUPERBUDGET lane where customers may have to wait a little bit longer.

Evaluation and Monitoring¶

The success of the market segmentation strategy must be assessed, and the market must be closely watched on a continuing basis, after the market segmentation analysis is finished and all strategic and tactical marketing actions have been carried out. For instance, section 3 members might begin to make more money and find that the MCSUPERBUDGET line is no longer appropriate for them. Existing market segments may undergo changes. However, alterations may also take place in the bigger market, for instance, if new rivals enter the industry. In order to detect changes that necessitate McDonald's management adjusting their strategy or tactical marketing in light of changing market circumstances, all potential sources of change must be closely examined.
